ld hide posting failures. REAL-INFRA: yes—real GitHub API call to post and verify the comment exists on the PR.","test_description":"Create a test PR with known findings from the linter. Run the pipeline (in GitHub Actions or equivalent environment), and verify that the actual posted PR comment groups findings by severity, with all findings present and formatted correctly. Validate the comment appears on the PR.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A pull request that touches 200 files completes analysis within the 10-minute Actions timeout.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure is timing/performance in the GitHub Actions environment. Unit tests with 200 items would catch O(n²) logic bugs but miss: (1) actual linter subprocess overhead (real static analysis tools are slow), (2) GitHub Actions environment overhead and resource constraints, (3) file I/O patterns on real filesystem, (4) network latency for API calls. Integration test with real linter on 200 files would help but wouldn't capture Actions-specific overhead. REAL-INFRA: yes—subprocess performance, filesystem I/O, and Actions environment constraints all matter.","test_description":"Create a test PR with exactly 200 changed files of realistic size and content. Run the linter step in a GitHub Actions environment and measure total runtime from start to posting comment. Verify it completes well under 10 minutes (e.g., under 5 minutes to ensure headroom).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the linter process crashes on a malformed file, the remaining files are still analyzed and results posted.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure has two parts: (1) exception handling when linter crashes—could be tested at Integration with real linter subprocess, 